He's so genuine.

26:40.700 --> 26:43.269
He's exactly why we
love "Troll 2."

26:43.302 --> 26:47.874
-I'm sure George Hardy is a
great dentist, but I respect

26:47.907 --> 26:49.075
him as an actor.

26:57.917 --> 27:02.889
-You know the trouble with
being psychologically

27:02.922 --> 27:06.726
disturbed is that
no matter how--

27:06.759 --> 27:10.663
how you get out of it and get
back to normalcy, as soon as

27:10.697 --> 27:14.200
you tell people you had mental
problems, they still treat you

27:14.233 --> 27:15.401
like you're nutty.

27:18.871 --> 27:22.274
I walked in ever decreasing
concentric circles until I

27:22.308 --> 27:25.812
found my head up my ass.

27:25.845 --> 27:29.882
I was sitting in my house on
13th East, and I couldn't

27:29.916 --> 27:32.685
decide whether to have
a hard boiled egg, a

27:32.719 --> 27:34.721
scrambled egg, or eggs.

27:34.754 --> 27:36.923
I couldn't make that decision.

27:36.956 --> 27:39.258
I was there, stuck.

27:39.291 --> 27:42.061
And a friend said, let me take
you to the hospital.

27:42.094 --> 27:46.032
And they took me right in.

27:46.065 --> 27:48.801
You know, I like to drive
without a seat belt.

27:48.835 --> 27:51.704
I really like the feeling of
driving without a seat belt.

27:54.273 --> 27:59.345
I was in the mental hospital at
the University of Utah, and

27:59.378 --> 28:02.214
they gave me days
off to go out.

28:02.248 --> 28:03.916
I called my agent.

28:03.950 --> 28:06.485
She said, they're shooting a
movie out in Park City, an

28:06.518 --> 28:08.287
Italian film company.

28:08.320 --> 28:09.922
And you go out there.

28:09.956 --> 28:11.958
I won't charge you if
you get the part.

28:11.991 --> 28:13.092
I went there.

28:13.125 --> 28:15.127
They said, come back again.

28:15.161 --> 28:17.029
And when I came back, they
said, the person who was

28:17.063 --> 28:19.131
supposed to do it
didn't show up.

28:19.165 --> 28:20.332
So you can do it.

28:27.539 --> 28:29.275
-Can I help you?

28:29.308 --> 28:30.943
-Coffee.

28:30.977 --> 28:32.444
-There's no coffee
here in Nilbog.

28:32.478 --> 28:35.481
It's the devil's drink.

28:35.514 --> 28:37.283
-Eggs.

28:37.316 --> 28:39.285
-[grunts]

28:39.318 --> 28:42.088
-You know, this is me.

28:42.121 --> 28:44.390
This is who I am.

28:44.423 --> 28:46.058
It's--

28:46.092 --> 28:48.360
you know, it's-- you know a lot
about people by the-- by

28:48.394 --> 28:51.397
the toys they have.

28:51.430 --> 28:52.799
These are my people.

28:55.134 --> 28:56.302
These are my people.

28:58.805 --> 29:01.373
If they were to run for office,
I'd vote for them.

29:01.407 --> 29:05.277
I smoked an enormous amount
of pot then to stay sane.

29:05.311 --> 29:08.214
And when I got on the set, I had
no idea what it all meant

29:08.247 --> 29:10.449
or what I was doing or
what I was saying.

29:10.482 --> 29:12.451
I don't know where we
went or what we did.

29:12.484 --> 29:16.388
And I have no idea of what
the total movie was.

29:16.422 --> 29:20.092
And I didn't see it until
20 years later.

29:20.126 --> 29:24.964
And I was amazed how
creepy I looked.

29:24.997 --> 29:29.068
I looked at that person,
who looked like this.

29:29.101 --> 29:31.537
And I realized I was
really troubled.

29:31.570 --> 29:33.906
I wasn't acting, I could
tell you that.

29:33.940 --> 29:35.174
I wasn't acting.

29:35.207 --> 29:38.477
That was a troubled
person talking.

29:38.510 --> 29:41.547
It was a terrible experience,
making that movie.

29:41.580 --> 29:43.249
It was always cold.

29:43.282 --> 29:45.051
It was always remote.

29:45.084 --> 29:48.587
And I remember there was a
little kid there, a little

29:48.620 --> 29:51.423
Mormon kid who was really
a pain in the ass.

29:51.457 --> 29:54.861
And he was the star, and
I wanted to kill him.

29:54.894 --> 29:57.997
And I was in the scene with him
where I said, try this.

29:58.030 --> 29:59.431
You'll like it.

29:59.465 --> 30:01.868
And I really wanted to feed
him that green stuff.

30:01.901 --> 30:04.837
I wanted to grab his head
and put it in it.

30:04.871 --> 30:06.605
I just couldn't stand him.

30:10.910 --> 30:13.212
The dentist, the one who played
the father was the

30:13.245 --> 30:16.048
Southern accent, called me.

30:16.082 --> 30:17.850
That's how I found
out about it.

30:17.884 --> 30:19.018
I was in the audience.

30:19.051 --> 30:21.153
I didn't want to go
up on the stage.

30:21.187 --> 30:24.256
-Don Packard showed up and was
sitting in the audience.

30:24.290 --> 30:25.925
-Yeah.

30:25.958 --> 30:27.026
He wasn't even, like,
necessarily wanting to be part

30:27.059 --> 30:28.160
of the Q&A.

30:28.194 --> 30:29.595
-We had to, like,
go and ask him.

30:29.628 --> 30:31.363
And he was like, oh, you want
me to-- oh, uh, OK.

30:31.397 --> 30:33.866
-Like, you flew to New York
just to watch this?

30:33.900 --> 30:37.503
-And the woman sitting next to
me said, you were great.

30:37.536 --> 30:38.871
She kept saying,
you were great.

30:38.905 --> 30:39.438
I--

30:39.471 --> 30:40.439
I was won over.

30:40.472 --> 30:42.041
-This is pretty incredible.

30:42.074 --> 30:43.275
I'm pretty giddy about it.

30:43.309 --> 30:45.978
Would the owner of the
general store--

30:46.012 --> 30:47.980
[cheering]

30:53.019 --> 30:53.419
-And I--

30:53.452 --> 30:54.921
I just--

30:54.954 --> 30:56.455
I went like this, and
everybody applauded.

30:56.488 --> 30:58.090
I was thrilled.

30:58.124 --> 30:59.225
I went like this.

30:59.258 --> 31:01.527
They all applauded
when I came out.

31:01.560 --> 31:05.097
And somehow, I was freed.

31:05.131 --> 31:06.565
I wasn't self conscious.

31:06.598 --> 31:09.668
It was really a golden
experience for me.

31:19.378 --> 31:22.048
I never felt that good in
all my life, really.

31:22.081 --> 31:26.052
I never was thrilled at being
who I was until that moment

31:26.085 --> 31:27.253
in-- in Manhattan.

31:35.427 --> 31:40.232
-Hello, my name is Mr. K. I'm
somewhere here in Austria in

31:40.266 --> 31:42.001
the middle of the woods.

31:42.034 --> 31:44.070
I'm not just cold,
I'm freezing.

31:44.103 --> 31:46.005
And I'm a troll.

31:46.038 --> 31:46.973
What else?

31:47.006 --> 31:48.507
I'm going to eat you.

31:48.540 --> 31:51.410
[growls]

31:51.443 --> 31:55.181
-My name is Kacper Radecki I'm
a "Troll 2" fan, and I live

31:55.214 --> 31:56.415
here in Austria.

31:56.448 --> 31:59.485
My desk in school is
full of "Troll 2."

31:59.518 --> 32:05.091
-I'm so excited that a movie can
mean that much to people

32:05.124 --> 32:07.293
without being pushed into it.

32:07.326 --> 32:09.728
The-- the audiences of
"Troll 2" had to have

32:09.761 --> 32:11.363
found it on their own.

32:11.397 --> 32:15.267
They had to be probably a
certain type of person who

32:15.301 --> 32:21.473
would rent videos that they've
never heard of and someone who

32:21.507 --> 32:23.976
watches movies more than once.

32:24.010 --> 32:26.212
-"Troll 2" is something
very special.

32:26.245 --> 32:29.115
It's a movie you can watch
1,000 times, and

32:29.148 --> 32:30.149
it won't get boring.

32:30.182 --> 32:32.985
It's just so perfectly bad.

32:33.019 --> 32:36.755
-I realized there's nothing more
intelligent that I could

32:36.788 --> 32:40.326
do as a 31-year-old man than
get a "Troll 2" tattoo.

32:44.730 --> 32:46.298
-I can't stand tattoos.

32:46.332 --> 32:47.499
But--

32:51.703 --> 32:53.172
JESSE (OFFSCREEN): It's
so interactive.

32:53.205 --> 32:55.541
You, um, personalize the film.

32:55.574 --> 32:58.510
And you take some sort
of ownership.

32:58.544 --> 33:01.080
-We bought a kit to make
actually like a profession

33:01.113 --> 33:02.048
latex mask.

33:02.081 --> 33:03.182
-Yeah, we like--

33:03.215 --> 33:04.216
-It's the first time,
you know.

33:04.250 --> 33:05.084
We'd never sculpted anything.

33:05.117 --> 33:06.252
-We'd never done it.

33:06.285 --> 33:07.219
I've never sculpted
any clay before.

33:10.656 --> 33:13.259
-It took about six weeks
to complete.

33:13.292 --> 33:15.061
We didn't know how it was going
to turn out, you know,

33:15.094 --> 33:17.196
being the first time we
made these costumes.

33:17.229 --> 33:19.731
-It turned out really well.

33:19.765 --> 33:22.668
-If I could get everyone's
attention, we're going to

33:22.701 --> 33:24.436
start the Trollympic game.

33:24.470 --> 33:27.806
So any-- everyone who wants to
participate, just come over

33:27.839 --> 33:28.407
here.

33:28.440 --> 33:29.408
-Go!

33:32.611 --> 33:33.379
-I would always invite
people over to watch

33:33.412 --> 33:34.780
"Troll 2" with me.

33:34.813 --> 33:36.648
So I don't know if that would
count as a party.

33:36.682 --> 33:39.251
But actual, like, official
"Troll 2" parties--

33:39.285 --> 33:40.452
this is my third.

33:46.558 --> 33:48.727
-Hi, my name's Adam Kourelis.

33:48.760 --> 33:52.298
I'm the one that brought
"Troll 2" to Iraq.

33:52.331 --> 33:55.267
-What I learned from this movie
is that whenever someone

33:55.301 --> 33:57.269
goes like this towards me, I--

33:57.303 --> 33:58.437
I--

33:58.470 --> 33:59.271
I won't eat whatever
they give me.

34:02.174 --> 34:04.376
-I basically made the
"Troll 2" video game

34:04.410 --> 34:06.745
because I love the movie.

34:06.778 --> 34:07.779
And I just--

34:07.813 --> 34:09.547
I wanted to make a good game.

34:09.581 --> 34:10.315
All right.

34:10.349 --> 34:11.483
We're at Nilbog.

34:11.516 --> 34:13.485
I'm shooting double
decker baloney

34:13.518 --> 34:16.155
sandwiches at the goblins.

34:16.188 --> 34:18.324
These are the strong ones.

34:18.357 --> 34:19.658
Yeah.

34:19.690 --> 34:23.228
-My friend Steve, also
a venue artist here--

34:23.262 --> 34:26.165
I showed him "Troll 2" probably
about like a year and

34:26.197 --> 34:28.667
a half ago, right around the
time we were starting "Guitar

34:28.699 --> 34:31.837
Hero II." And he made, you know,
one of his levels the

34:31.870 --> 34:32.871
high school gym.

34:32.904 --> 34:34.473
And he called it Nilbog High.

34:34.505 --> 34:36.342
You know, and we-- we all
that thought was great.

34:36.375 --> 34:41.147
-I actually wrote the, uh,
sequel, "Troll 2, Monstrous

34:41.179 --> 34:43.681
Beings." This is a
close figure on

34:43.715 --> 34:44.616
the side of the road.

34:44.650 --> 34:45.751
Michael gets on the CB.

34:45.784 --> 34:47.518
And he says, hey,
son, to Elliott.

34:47.553 --> 34:48.754
Elliott says, yes, dad.

34:48.786 --> 34:49.521
I hate--

34:49.554 --> 34:51.257
I hate to see--

34:51.290 --> 34:53.559
-If this movie is resonating so
strongly with all of these

34:53.592 --> 34:56.295
people, what is beneath the
surface that is this kind of

34:56.328 --> 35:01.300
unconscious thing that is
getting under our skin?

35:01.333 --> 35:03.469
-I don't think it's the
worst film ever made.

35:03.502 --> 35:06.638
I have seen worse
films than this.

35:06.672 --> 35:08.474
But it's--

35:08.507 --> 35:09.641
it's not necessarily
that it's bad.

35:09.675 --> 35:10.609
It's odd.

35:10.642 --> 35:11.543
It's really odd.

35:11.577 --> 35:13.312
It doesn't make sense.

35:13.345 --> 35:16.148
And it's like, a lot of bad
movies, you get the impression

35:16.182 --> 35:16.882
that people that make them
just didn't know

35:16.915 --> 35:18.617
how to make a film.

35:18.650 --> 35:21.553
This is like the people knew
how to make a film but had

35:21.587 --> 35:23.555
suffered quite a heavy
blow to the head.

35:23.589 --> 35:25.491
-When the time comes,
you light the wick

35:25.524 --> 35:27.226
and throw the bottle.

35:27.259 --> 35:29.461
I'll create some confusion
with this.

35:29.495 --> 35:31.230
JESSE (OFFSCREEN):
It's genuine.

35:31.263 --> 35:36.702
There's no irony going on, a
film that genuinely expresses

35:36.735 --> 35:41.473
a story, a totally whacked
story too.

35:41.507 --> 35:44.310
-There's sandwiches for
tonight in here.

35:44.343 --> 35:48.380
It will go easier
if you eat them.

35:48.414 --> 35:52.218
-The best bad movies are not
deliberately bad, always.

35:52.251 --> 35:55.187
You know, like, the most fondly
remembered stinkers are

35:55.221 --> 35:57.723
the movies that people went all
out, and they tried their

35:57.756 --> 35:59.291
best and totally failed,
but gloriously.

36:02.294 --> 36:05.664
-What we want from a film
is honesty and--

36:05.697 --> 36:07.366
and sincerity.

36:07.399 --> 36:08.734
We want to feel like these
people really care about what

36:08.767 --> 36:10.869
they're making, even if
it is really awful.

36:10.902 --> 36:14.773
That's why Ed Wood is still so
highly regarded, because Ed

36:14.806 --> 36:16.708
Wood wasn't just making trash.

36:16.742 --> 36:19.211
He really believed in
what he was making.

36:19.245 --> 36:20.446
And that makes a
big difference.

36:20.479 --> 36:21.980
You know, I see some
of these films.

36:22.013 --> 36:22.848
And I think, these are people
who have just thrown this

36:22.881 --> 36:24.316
together cynically.

36:24.350 --> 36:34.393
But there isn't a cynicism
in "Troll 2."

36:34.393 --> 36:44.403
But there isn't a cynicism
in "Troll 2."

