But it was run down
quite a bit then.

46:58.016 --> 47:00.118
-They picked the right house.

47:00.151 --> 47:02.220
-I guarantee you, there's some
mental insanity here, some

47:02.253 --> 47:04.022
mental insanity.

47:04.055 --> 47:12.964
So this is really the perfect
spot for "Troll 2." I

47:12.998 --> 47:14.199
remember, I come
out like this.

47:14.232 --> 47:15.633
ROBERT (OFFSCREEN):
How are you doing?

47:15.666 --> 47:18.469
-And I come out and kind
of go, oh, god.

47:18.503 --> 47:20.305
And then I go--

47:20.338 --> 47:21.506
and for some reason--

47:28.113 --> 47:30.348
-OK, OK.

47:30.381 --> 47:32.017
-How-- question.

47:32.050 --> 47:34.986
I can remember sitting down with
Michael and Connie and

47:35.020 --> 47:37.355
Margo, and we would
take the script.

47:37.388 --> 47:40.325
And we would try to decipher
what it meant.

47:40.358 --> 47:45.330
We would sit there for hours,
looking at this script and try

47:45.363 --> 47:47.465
to do, you know, an analysis
on the scenes.

47:47.498 --> 47:49.200
And we couldn't do it.

47:49.234 --> 47:52.670
How did I know that there was
a fire extinguisher right

47:52.703 --> 47:54.039
there the whole time?

47:59.610 --> 48:01.212
-And I thought, well,
this guy's famous.

48:01.246 --> 48:02.948
He knows what the
hell he's doing.

48:02.981 --> 48:04.382
And I mean, I was
just, whatever.

48:04.415 --> 48:05.516
You know?

48:05.550 --> 48:07.585
[laughing]

48:07.618 --> 48:09.520
-We sat out here on this curb
in front of the house--

48:09.554 --> 48:11.356
Connie and I-- during
our break.

48:11.389 --> 48:12.590
And we were looking
at this script.

48:12.623 --> 48:14.459
And she said, I'm really
uncomfortable

48:14.492 --> 48:16.261
with the nuts line.

48:16.294 --> 48:19.630
We came up with something that
was, uh, we thought, more PG.

48:19.664 --> 48:21.699
Then we tracked down Claudio,
and we said, Claudio, we

48:21.732 --> 48:24.335
really think this will
work better.

48:24.369 --> 48:25.503
It's a little more PG.

48:25.536 --> 48:27.105
This is how American
teenagers talk.

48:27.138 --> 48:30.641
And he said, I know how American
teenagers talk.

48:30.675 --> 48:33.044
This is how American
teenagers talk.

48:33.078 --> 48:34.079
-That's not how you do that.

48:34.112 --> 48:35.246
That's not American.

48:35.280 --> 48:36.481
And he would always
say that to me.

48:36.514 --> 48:38.016
I don't know if he said
that to you a lot.

48:38.049 --> 48:39.985
But he would always tell
me what was American.

48:40.018 --> 48:41.987
[music playing]

48:49.394 --> 48:51.496
-There was a lot of times I've
seen they were trying to add

48:51.529 --> 48:54.365
something or trying to make
it seem a little bit

48:54.399 --> 48:55.533
more natural to us.

48:55.566 --> 48:58.203
But it-- it--

48:58.236 --> 49:02.173
he had a real-- you know, had
a real vision of what he

49:02.207 --> 49:03.508
wanted to see.

49:03.541 --> 49:06.544
-Michael, who are the goblins?

49:06.577 --> 49:07.445
No, no, I say--

49:07.478 --> 49:08.113
-Who are the goblins?

49:08.146 --> 49:09.014
-I say--

49:09.047 --> 49:10.281
I say like, Michael--

49:13.484 --> 49:15.486
you can-- you are an actor.

49:15.520 --> 49:16.221
You cannot laugh.

49:16.254 --> 49:16.754
-OK.

49:16.787 --> 49:17.455
I will not.

49:17.488 --> 49:18.356
I will not.

49:18.389 --> 49:19.124
-You must be serious.

49:19.157 --> 49:19.657
OK?

49:19.690 --> 49:20.625
-All right.

49:20.658 --> 49:24.229
-Say, who are the goblins?

49:24.262 --> 49:25.430
-The goblins?

49:35.273 --> 49:37.508
-That was nice.

49:37.542 --> 49:40.545
-For the goblins, they weren't
looking for talent.

49:40.578 --> 49:43.514
You know, we didn't even have
to match the brilliant level

49:43.548 --> 49:45.716
of acting that was going on
in the rest of the film.

49:45.750 --> 49:47.085
They just--

49:47.118 --> 49:48.153
they were just looking
at heights.

49:48.186 --> 49:49.587
-I remember them
putting this--

49:49.620 --> 49:53.491
almost like a burlap
bag shirt on us.

49:53.524 --> 49:55.193
And they put gloves on us.

49:55.226 --> 49:59.230
And the gloves were way
longer than my hands.

49:59.264 --> 50:03.701
And so they kind of would tape
them on to the burlap bag.

50:03.734 --> 50:06.371
I had no clue what the
movie was about.

50:06.404 --> 50:09.074
-It was kind of hard to get a
straight answer as to exactly

50:09.107 --> 50:11.709
what the nature of
the project was.

50:11.742 --> 50:13.544
But we were excited.

50:13.578 --> 50:15.213
We were told it was
low budget.

50:15.246 --> 50:18.049
But, you know, we-- we know that
low budget is kind of a

50:18.083 --> 50:19.350
relative term.

50:19.384 --> 50:21.119
After a few days, we
realized this was

50:21.152 --> 50:23.421
really, really low budget.

50:23.454 --> 50:27.592
And by, I think it was probably
three days into

50:27.625 --> 50:28.759
shooting that we kind of--

50:28.793 --> 50:30.361
-You will remember
the director.

50:30.395 --> 50:31.096
-Yes.

50:31.129 --> 50:32.330
Oh, Claudio.

50:32.363 --> 50:34.065
-How are you?

50:34.099 --> 50:36.201
-As we started shooting more
and more, it started to get

50:36.234 --> 50:38.469
more confusing rather
than less.

50:38.503 --> 50:41.739
And it was like each day we were
on the set, we knew less

50:41.772 --> 50:44.075
about what this movie was
actually supposed to be.

50:44.109 --> 50:47.212
-And action.

50:47.245 --> 50:48.413
-You see this writing?

50:52.350 --> 50:53.651
[laughing]

50:53.684 --> 50:54.552
CLAUDIO (OFFSCREEN): Come
on, say the line!

50:54.585 --> 50:55.786
-You know what it means?

50:58.656 --> 50:59.790
Hospitality!

51:05.363 --> 51:06.731
And you can't piss
on hospitality.

51:06.764 --> 51:08.299
I won't allow it!

51:08.333 --> 51:09.567
-What are you going to
do to me, daddy?

51:09.600 --> 51:11.302
-OK, Joshua.

51:11.336 --> 51:12.870
You want to know what it feels
like to have hunger pains?

51:12.903 --> 51:15.406
Well, I'm tightening my belt
buckle by one notch so I don't

51:15.440 --> 51:17.375
feel hunger pains.

51:17.408 --> 51:18.709
[laughing]

51:18.743 --> 51:19.677
-No, no.

51:19.710 --> 51:20.678
Be serious.

51:20.711 --> 51:22.313
Repeat.

51:22.347 --> 51:24.715
-There was a recurring problem
on the set that was this

51:24.749 --> 51:27.418
language barrier that we
all had to deal with.

51:27.452 --> 51:28.653
-One of the Italian ADs--

51:28.686 --> 51:30.255
-Right.

51:30.288 --> 51:32.623
---said, if you would all please
to be following me

51:32.657 --> 51:34.259
upstairs now.

51:34.292 --> 51:35.560
And we were out there in the
middle of the canyon.

51:35.593 --> 51:36.694
There was no--

51:36.727 --> 51:37.828
there were no stairs
or anything.

51:37.862 --> 51:39.297
I mean, just going
up this slope.

51:47.772 --> 51:52.477
-When I call you, and I say
action, you come, and you do.

51:52.510 --> 51:54.445
You go around.

51:54.479 --> 51:56.614
Go around, and after,
you come up.

51:56.647 --> 51:57.748
OK.

51:57.782 --> 52:00.251
We start with one
with the other.

52:00.285 --> 52:01.152
Oh, eat.

52:01.186 --> 52:02.420
Oh, finally, we can eat.

52:02.453 --> 52:03.254
Oh, OK.

52:03.288 --> 52:04.755
Blah, blah, blah.

52:04.789 --> 52:07.658
GEORGE (OFFSCREEN): Claudio
speaks a lot better English

52:07.692 --> 52:09.394
than he did 18 years ago.

52:09.427 --> 52:10.528
I mean, there was no way we
could understand things like

52:10.561 --> 52:11.762
that last time he
worked with us.

52:11.796 --> 52:13.464
-I--

52:13.498 --> 52:15.900
I really couldn't understand
what they wanted me to do.

52:15.933 --> 52:17.568
-Open, open, open.

52:17.602 --> 52:18.469
Come on, come on.

52:18.503 --> 52:19.270
Open and say the line.

52:19.304 --> 52:19.904
Say the line.

52:19.937 --> 52:21.272
Say the line.

52:21.306 --> 52:23.374
-The Italians did kind
of annoy me.

52:23.408 --> 52:24.675
They're really intense.

52:24.709 --> 52:28.546
They were really intense
people, very bossy.

52:28.579 --> 52:31.382
I feel about as confused as I
did when we were doing it.

52:31.416 --> 52:32.250
-Come on.

52:32.283 --> 52:32.883
Don't talk with me.

52:32.917 --> 52:33.718
There is a camera.

52:33.751 --> 52:34.885
Don't laugh.

52:34.919 --> 52:36.487
Stay serious.

52:36.521 --> 52:38.423
-I had a yellow shirt, and
it had a logo on it and

52:38.456 --> 52:39.857
a logo on the back.

52:39.890 --> 52:41.859
But halfway through filming,
they lost my shirt.

52:41.892 --> 52:44.829
And we'd already filmed like
half of my scenes.

52:44.862 --> 52:46.331
And so they're like,
oh, that's fine.

52:46.364 --> 52:47.898
Go buy a yellow shirt.

52:47.932 --> 52:49.867
And I was just like, you want
me to buy the yellow shirt?

52:49.900 --> 52:51.869
I'm like, isn't there
like someone to go

52:51.902 --> 52:53.204
buy the yellow shirt?

52:53.238 --> 52:54.239
Isn't there someone
in wardrobe?

52:54.272 --> 52:54.939
They're like, no.

52:54.972 --> 52:56.341
Go buy a yellow shirt.

52:56.374 --> 52:57.542
-They took my shoes--

52:57.575 --> 53:00.745
mind you, my shoes, not
theirs, my black

53:00.778 --> 53:02.547
Converse high tops.

53:02.580 --> 53:05.950
And they screwed them into the
base of the pot, where I stood

53:05.983 --> 53:08.619
for almost 14 hours
in make up.

53:30.441 --> 53:32.009
-We really were trying
to make a good movie.

53:32.042 --> 53:33.411
We really were.

53:33.444 --> 53:37.415
Um, it just didn't turn
out that way.

53:37.448 --> 53:40.618
-I've always loved bad movies.

53:40.651 --> 53:42.453
And I always thought,
god, it'd be great

53:42.487 --> 53:43.988
to be in a bad movie.

53:44.021 --> 53:47.392
But I had no idea when I was
making it that I was making

53:47.425 --> 53:48.993
that bad a movie.

53:49.026 --> 53:52.830
So it's wonderful to find out
that yeah, I made a bad movie,

53:52.863 --> 53:56.000
a really bad movie that
got to be famous.

54:00.671 --> 54:02.307
GEORGE (OFFSCREEN): This
is very familiar.

54:02.340 --> 54:05.410
You go up here and take a right,
go off to the right.

54:05.443 --> 54:07.945
I remember when I filmed "Troll
2," I would go pick up

54:07.978 --> 54:11.649
Margo and take her to the set.

54:11.682 --> 54:16.654
And so I kind of remember a
little bit of where she lives.

54:16.687 --> 54:22.827
It says, no trespassing except
for US mail, no dogs, no

54:22.860 --> 54:24.329
literature.

54:24.362 --> 54:26.331
Do not ring the bell except
by documented

54:26.364 --> 54:27.898
request by the owner.

54:27.932 --> 54:31.702
Violators will be prosecuted.

54:31.736 --> 54:33.304
Wow.

54:33.338 --> 54:33.871
Oh, god.

54:33.904 --> 54:34.705
This is crazy.

54:34.739 --> 54:35.540
What in the world?

54:35.573 --> 54:36.807
What are we doing?

54:36.841 --> 54:38.509
-What's the worst thing
that could happen?

54:38.543 --> 54:40.077
-That she comes to the door
with a gun, or she shoots

54:40.110 --> 54:41.879
through the door with a gun.

54:41.912 --> 54:43.481
I mean, she could have
mental issues.

54:43.514 --> 54:45.082
A bullet comes through
the door.

54:45.115 --> 54:46.951
-George, don't say that.

54:46.984 --> 54:48.919
-Well, that's the worst
that can happen.

54:48.953 --> 54:49.954
MICHAEL (OFFSCREEN):
You want to do it?

54:49.987 --> 54:50.988
-Yeah, it's like pulling
a tooth.

54:51.021 --> 54:51.922
Let's just go ahead and do it.

54:59.664 --> 55:01.432
MARGO (OFFSCREEN): Who is it?

55:01.466 --> 55:03.734
-It's Michael and--
and George Hardy.

55:03.768 --> 55:04.935
We--

55:04.969 --> 55:06.671
is it you, Margo?

55:06.704 --> 55:07.405
MARGO (OFFSCREEN): Yeah.

55:07.438 --> 55:07.938
-Hey, Margo.

55:07.972 --> 55:08.939
It's George.

55:08.973 --> 55:10.908
I was in "Troll 2" with you.

55:10.941 --> 55:11.642
-Hey.

55:11.676 --> 55:12.377
It's Margo.

55:12.410 --> 55:13.344
-Hey, Margo.

55:13.378 --> 55:14.044
MARGO (OFFSCREEN): Oh, hi.

55:14.078 --> 55:15.646
What are you doing here?

55:15.680 --> 55:16.514
-We--

55:16.547 --> 55:17.014
we are--

55:17.047 --> 55:18.048
we came--

55:18.082 --> 55:18.783
George actually came in front.

55:18.816 --> 55:19.917
I'm Michael.

55:19.950 --> 55:20.818
I played your son
in the movie.

55:20.851 --> 55:21.419
MARGO (OFFSCREEN): Hi.

55:21.452 --> 55:22.387
Hi.

55:22.420 --> 55:23.020
-Do you remember Michael?

55:23.053 --> 55:23.921
-Do you remember?

55:23.954 --> 55:24.555
MARGO (OFFSCREEN): Yeah.

55:24.589 --> 55:25.556
-Yeah.

55:25.590 --> 55:26.591
And I-- do you remember me?

55:26.624 --> 55:27.358
MARGO (OFFSCREEN): Yeah, I do.

55:27.392 --> 55:28.359
-How are you?

55:28.393 --> 55:28.893
MARGO (OFFSCREEN): I'm good.

55:28.926 --> 55:29.527
How are you?

55:29.560 --> 55:30.828
-Good.

55:30.861 --> 55:31.429
MARGO (OFFSCREEN): You
just came to say hi?

55:31.462 --> 55:31.862
-Yeah.

55:31.896 --> 55:32.830
We did.

55:32.863 --> 55:33.598
MARGO (OFFSCREEN): Crazy.

55:33.631 --> 55:34.465
-I don't know--

55:34.499 --> 55:34.899
I know, it is crazy.

55:34.932 --> 55:35.933
-We--

55:35.966 --> 55:37.034
I don't know if you've known--

55:37.067 --> 55:38.769
-We've been trying
to find you.

55:38.803 --> 55:39.537
You're the last one of all of
our cast members to find.

55:39.570 --> 55:40.505
We couldn't--

55:40.538 --> 55:41.406
of the major cast members.

55:41.439 --> 55:42.407
We couldn't find you.

55:42.440 --> 55:43.908
So now, are you working now?

55:43.941 --> 55:46.110
Or are you-- are you doing
auditions for anything now?

55:46.143 --> 55:47.512
Or--

55:47.545 --> 55:49.079
-Well, I haven't been
auditioning in

55:49.113 --> 55:51.982
the last, like, year.

55:52.016 --> 55:55.052
I don't really have an
agent right now.

55:55.085 --> 55:56.921
I did have one.

55:56.954 --> 55:59.089
You know, I'm just kind of
like edging into it.

55:59.123 --> 56:03.394
I'm waiting for things in my
life to kind of settle down a

56:03.428 --> 56:03.828
little bit.

56:03.861 --> 56:05.463
-Sure.

56:05.496 --> 56:10.435
-Because I just-- it's
complicated now for me to do

56:10.468 --> 56:10.968
things.

56:11.001 --> 56:11.869
-Sure, yeah.

56:11.902 --> 56:12.870
-It's just complicated.

56:12.903 --> 56:14.171
It's just complicated.

56:14.204 --> 56:17.007
I learn all the time new
things about acting.

56:17.041 --> 56:19.877
Even though I may not be acting
every single day or

56:19.910 --> 56:24.982
doing parts every single day,
I watch movies, and I take

56:25.015 --> 56:27.752
mental notes about what I
liked about what those

56:27.785 --> 56:29.420
characters are doing.

56:29.454 --> 56:31.055
And very often, I write it down
on a piece of paper and

56:31.088 --> 56:33.424
stick it on my mirror
in my bedroom.

56:33.458 --> 56:35.593
And then I look at it,
you know, until it

56:35.626 --> 56:36.927
sinks into my head.

56:36.961 --> 56:37.928
Hold on.

56:37.962 --> 56:38.896
Let me get a drink of water.

56:38.929 --> 56:39.864
Let me get you some water.

56:39.897 --> 56:41.165
There's some warm water.

56:41.198 --> 56:42.800
That will help you
out a little bit.

56:42.833 --> 56:44.735
OK.

56:44.769 --> 56:46.537
Taking care of my
mother is easy.

56:46.571 --> 56:47.872
She's easy.

56:47.905 --> 56:51.842
I feel sad for her having
to not be able to

56:51.876 --> 56:53.644
use one of her legs.

56:53.678 --> 56:55.880
I feel sad for her because she's
always been acting her

56:55.913 --> 56:56.881
whole entire life.

56:56.914 --> 56:58.683
You doing OK?

56:58.716 --> 57:00.451
We're going to have dinner
pretty soon.

57:00.485 --> 57:01.919
They're almost done.

57:01.952 --> 57:04.154
This has lasted quite a lot
longer than I thought.

57:04.188 --> 57:04.989
-Yes.

57:05.022 --> 57:06.491
-Yeah.

57:06.524 --> 57:07.858
But we're going to have
dinner pretty soon.

57:07.892 --> 57:08.893
And then we'll-- we'll get
ready to go to bed.

57:17.635 --> 57:22.039
I just made it me.

57:22.072 --> 57:28.846
I just did it the way I would
do it because I felt that we

57:28.879 --> 57:31.516
were just like one
person, you know?

57:31.549 --> 57:34.485
And I could just take the words
and let them come out of

57:34.519 --> 57:36.887
my mouth just the way
I would do it.

57:36.921 --> 57:39.790
And so it became a really
simple thing.

57:39.824 --> 57:41.859
-Joshua, start singing.

57:41.892 --> 57:42.893
Come on.

57:42.927 --> 57:44.028
Sing that song I like so much.

57:44.061 --> 57:46.230
-I don't feel like
singing, mom.

57:46.263 --> 57:48.198
-Just sing.

57:48.232 --> 57:52.002
-(SINGING) Row, row, row your
boat, gently down the stream.

57:52.036 --> 57:53.871
-(SINGING) Merrily, merrily,
merrily, merrily,

57:53.904 --> 57:55.606
life is but a dream.

57:55.640 --> 58:00.244
-I remember you crying out in
that voice that just sent

58:00.277 --> 58:02.513
shudders through my spine.

58:02.547 --> 58:06.116
(WHISPERING) Mom, mom.

58:06.150 --> 58:08.085
-They're eating my mom.

58:16.827 --> 58:20.097
-And I really believed that
you had lost your mother.

58:25.903 --> 58:27.071
It was great.

58:29.974 --> 58:32.109
I don't really feel sad that
I never had children.

58:32.142 --> 58:33.611
It's not that I don't
like children.

58:33.644 --> 58:35.179
I like children.

58:35.212 --> 58:40.117
But I really don't think that
I could be a real life mom.

58:40.150 --> 58:43.921
Joshua, sing that song
I like so much.

58:43.954 --> 58:46.123
-But mom, I don't feel
like singing.

58:46.156 --> 58:49.159
-Come on, sing.

58:49.193 --> 58:51.962
-(SINGING) Row, row, row
your boat, gently--

58:51.996 --> 58:53.864
[laughing]

58:53.898 --> 58:56.901
-Why can't-- are you laughing
at my voice?

58:56.934 --> 58:58.836
-No, I'm laughing
at me because--

58:58.869 --> 58:59.837
[laughing]

58:59.870 --> 59:01.271
-I know.

59:01.305 --> 59:05.175
That's what the choir
instructor did.

59:05.209 --> 59:07.344
-I just never imagined
we'd be doing this.

59:07.377 --> 59:08.245
OK.

59:08.278 --> 59:09.714
You ready?

59:09.747 --> 59:11.081
Let's do it again.

59:11.115 --> 59:12.617
[SINGING IN ROUNDS - "ROW,
ROW, ROW YOUR BOAT"]

59:22.693 --> 59:25.663
-After I watched the movie, and
I saw it, and it was over,

59:25.696 --> 59:27.331
and I turned off the TV,
I just sat back.

59:27.364 --> 59:29.834
And I said, wow,
this is great.

59:29.867 --> 59:30.901
This is really great.

59:30.935 --> 59:32.336
It was really good.

59:32.369 --> 59:38.208
It's a simple, elegant, down
to earth, real, natural,

59:38.242 --> 59:39.944
actor, actor movie.

59:39.977 --> 59:43.313
You know, most of the movies
that are around now are fast

59:43.347 --> 59:47.652
paced and car chases and car
crashes and explosions and

59:47.685 --> 59:51.789
fires and murders and blood
and gore and killing.

59:51.822 --> 59:55.025
But you compare our movie to a
Katharine Hepburn and Humphrey

59:55.059 --> 01:00:01.766
Bogart movie, and it fits in
because our movie was all

01:00:01.799 --> 01:00:05.670
about people and the experiences
those people were

01:00:05.703 --> 01:00:10.107
experiencing, just as
"Casablanca" and those movies

01:00:10.140 --> 01:00:13.043
are about people and the
experiences they're

01:00:13.077 --> 01:00:14.845
experiencing.

